                        "type": "0",
                        "version": 0,
                        "content": "What should the nurse teach a client about an expected outcome of nesiritide (Natrecor) administration?\n",
                        "subjectId": "ad5ab04c79144c0ea9b83385308c3b1d",
                        "difficultyIds": "80db17ea97ed8fdcd1b6b9666390fca1",
                        "difficulty": "考试范围-Applying 应用",
                        "textAnalysis": "Rationale:\nNesiritide is a recombinant version of human B-type natriuretic peptide, which vasodilates arteries and veins. It is used for the treatment of decompensated heart failure, increases renal glomerular filtration, and increases urine output. The remaining options are incorrect about the intended effect of this medication.\n\nTest-Taking Strategy:\nFocus on the subject, intended effect of nesiritide. Nesiritide does not have antidysrhythmic properties. Dysrhythmias may be a side effect of the medication, so option 2 needs to be eliminated. Eliminate option 3 because the medication is a vasodilator and causes a decrease in blood pressure. Eliminate option 4 because the medication decreases pulmonary capillary wedge pressure.\n \n\nClient Needs: Physiological Integrity\nClinical Judgment/Cognitive Skill(s): Take Action\nCognitive Ability: Applying\nContent Area: Pharmacology: Cardiovascular: Vasodilators\nHealth Problem: Adult Health: Cardiovascular: Heart Failure\nIntegrated Process: Teaching and Learning\nPriority Concepts: Perfusion, Patient Education\nStrategies: Subject\n",
                        "id": "cf4c380de34947c0adc3d352ff69c1c5",
                        "mark": "0",
                        "collectionState": "0"
                    }
                ]
            },
